> On Wed, 17 Apr 2002 ballantiner(-at-)uncw.edu wrote:
> 
> well being of the "take only the engine out" school I don''t usually take
> out the transmission yoke bolts so I don't support the tranny extra at all 
>  
> and since I have an automatic my front support is a big flat plate into a
> slot, so unless I pull the tranny rearward or unbolt the plate the tranny
> isn't going anywhere.  not sure about the manual tranny mounts
> 
> Bob
> 
> > > If you find that you have to support the tranny on your Type 
> > > 4 Bus, you have
> > > a serious problem somewhere.  On the Type 4, the tranny is 
> > > hung from the
> > > chassis at the rear by two big bolts.  No tranny support is 
> > > needed, and the
> > > transmission does not move when you remove the engine.
> >  
> > 
> > It's not the rear of the tranny that needs support, it's the 
> > front (so says Bentley anyway.) My theory was that the engine
> > and bearer (and the 2 big bolts) held the tranny in place (and
> > correctly aligned) while the engine is in, and removing the 
> > engine puts more of the weight of the tranny on the front mount, 
> > which may not be designed for that much pressure? 
> > 
> > I was just following Bentley's recommendation.  I'd love to skip
> > that step if it's not needed.  I'm a T2 novice so when I read the
> > "make sure to support the front of the tranny" part in Bentley, at
> > first I thought "I never had to do this with a Beetle" but then I had
> > had visions of my tranny dropping and breaking on the concrete floor
> > so I just went along with what the book said.
> > 
> > Rob
